CRIMEAN-CONGO HEMORRHAGIC FEVER - ASIA (02): IRAQ (DHI QAR)
***********************************************************
A ProMED-mail post
http://www.promedmail.org
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
http://www.isid.org

[1]
Date: Mon 25 Apr 2022
Source: Al Mada [in Arabic, machine trans., edited]
https://almadapaper.net/view.php?cat=263647


The Division of Communicable Diseases Control in the Dhi Qar Health Department announced unprecedented rates of [infection with Crimean-Congo] hemorrhagic fever, and has called for the activation of veterinary measures to prevent the spread of the disease.

The local government accused the Ministry of Agriculture of not providing resources for the control of parasitic insects that carry [the Crimean-Congo] hemorrhagic fever. Haider Ali Hantoush, Director of the Communicable Diseases Control Division, told Al-Mada that "since the middle of last year 2021 until today [25 Apr 2022], unprecedented and unexpected rates of [the Crimean-Congo] hemorrhagic fever have been recorded", noting that the total infections (cases) amounted to 30, including 10 deaths during the same period."

Hantoush added that "the infections have resulted in 16 cases and 7 deaths during the 2nd half of 2021, 14 confirmed cases and 3 deaths during the first 3rd of 2022," stressing that "deaths constitute a 3rd of the number of the infected." He pointed out that "infections with hemorrhagic fever increased during the past year [2021] and the current year [2022]," revealing that "the last case and death recorded in the past was in 2018, while the years 2019, 2020 and the first half of 2021 did not witness any infection."

Hantoush pointed out that "infections began to escalate during the 2nd half of 2021 and have continued so far to record unprecedented rates." He stressed that "[the Crimean-Congo] hemorrhagic fever is a serious disease with a death rate of 40%."

Regarding the ways of transmission of the disease, Hantoush said, "The disease is a viral disease of animal origin and is transmitted in particular through livestock, as animals are considered carriers of the disease and are not affected much by it. Those who deal with animal meat are [can be] infected, as it is transmitted through it." Hantoush also added "the groups most vulnerable to infection are livestock breeders and butchers, in addition to those who deal with meat from infected livestock" stressing that "some women were infected as a result of cutting fresh meat from an infected animal." The infections [cases] recorded this year [2022] are distributed among the districts of Suq Al-Shuyoukh, Al-Rifai, Ur district, and one case in the Al-Thawra area in Nasiriyah.

Regarding preventive and curative measures, Hantoush commented, "The governorate's administration has previously formed a committee to follow up on [the Crimean-Congo] hemorrhagic fever, headed by the assistant governor, Abbas Al-Khuzai, the departments of veterinary, agriculture, municipalities, health, environment and the police command," stressing that "an integrated isolation ward has been allocated for infected patients in Al-Hussein Teaching Hospital."

Hantoush indicated that "the 1st preventive measure is to control the tick, which is the 1st carrier of the disease", noting that "this measure is currently unavailable because the aforementioned insect control materials were not sufficiently made available by the Ministry of Agriculture."

The assistant governor of Dhi Qar for planning affairs, who heads the agricultural committee in Dhi Qar, Faisal Al-Sharifi, told Al-Mada, that "the veterinary departments have taken measures to limit the foci of infection for the purpose of controlling the disease and limiting its transmission," noting that "the main problem lies in the fact that the disease is a communicable disease."

Regarding the failure to provide materials to combat the tick that transmits the disease, Al-Sharifi said that "providing and importing materials involved in combating this insect is one of the exclusive prerogatives of the Ministry of Agriculture and local governments have no right to import them." Al-Sharifi stressed that "the ministry has not provided them yet, and the local government's budget does not provide for the purchase of these materials." He noted, "The Ministry of Agriculture asks the governorates to provide money for this purpose and deposit it in the ministry's account so that it can buy them and then distribute them to the governorates, and this is a long process and not consistent with the requirements of the emergency situation that relates to people's lives."

Al-Sharifi revealed that "the ministerial restrictions are very complicated and the high rates of infection require quick and urgent measures to limit the spread and exacerbation of the disease."

He urged "the Ministry of Agriculture to take immediate measures to provide materials to control the insects that transmit the disease, because the disease can be transmitted even through the bite of stray dogs, and here lies the danger", he said.

The director of the veterinary hospital in Dhi Qar, Imad Diab Al-Nassar, revealed a number of measures taken by the crisis cell recently formed by the governorate to limit the transmission of the disease. Diab spoke to Al-Mada about "taking a number of decisions, including the restrictions on the entry and exit of animals to and from the governorate" as well as not to move animals from endemic areas to healthy ones." He pointed out that "a decision was taken to combat random slaughter and to limit the process of slaughtering livestock to official slaughterhouses."

[Byline: Hussein al-Amil]

--
