******
[3]
Date: Wed 27 Apr 2022
Source: Dubai Week [edited]
https://www.dubaiweek.ae/bleeding-fever-wave-in-iraq-18-injuries-and-4-deaths/


Saif al-Badr, a spokesman for the Ministry of Health, told the official Iraqi News Agency (INA) that Sick Bleeding fever [cases] has left 18 wounded and 4 dead across Iraq.

Al-Badr called on the people to "be vigilant and follow preventive measures to avoid this dangerous disease."

Many viruses cause hemorrhagic fever, and the disease can sometimes be simple, but sometimes it can be life threatening if it is known to be transmitted to humans from certain animals and insects, and the infection can be transmitted from one person to another.

Most of the injuries [infections] are concentrated in the Dhi Qar Governorate in the south of the country, where the ministry announced on Monday [25 Apr 2022] that it would send a high-level team led by the director general of the public health department. Measures were taken in collaboration with the local government in the governorate, ministries and other bodies.

Experts say the Garh has registered 30 cases since the middle of last year [2021], with 10 deaths, and officials involved in the governorate have launched a campaign to control the red meat markets.

Audit campaigns
---------------
A statement from the health media said, "Health control groups in the Nazarene First Division are continuing their control campaigns to pursue meat shops that sell red meat in markets and neighborhoods to Shamia." These measures are preventive conditions necessary for the health and safety of citizens.

A veterinarian at the governorate said, "The disease started to spread last year [2021] and many deaths and sicknesses were recorded in the city and other cities, but it is strange that the official procedures of the Ministry of Health have not been implemented. There is a need nationally to combat the disease and strengthen veterinary services with basic materials, initiating monitoring committees to monitor animal slaughterhouses and complying with safety recommendations."

The doctor, who did not want to be named, told Sky News Arabia, "The disease is not dangerous in its early stages, but if it spreads rapidly, it will be difficult to control and prevent, especially in the absence of the necessary vaccine."

In the same vein, several Iraqi governorates have announced rapid measures to prevent the spread of the disease and its spread.

Kirkuk Governorate Health Director Nabil Hamdi said, "The Governorate will launch a campaign to prevent hemorrhagic fever, especially after the outbreak of the disease in Dhi Qar Governorate."

He stressed in a press release that "the investigation into the issue of hemorrhagic fever in Kirkuk is ongoing and we will conduct a workshop to spread awareness and culture about the spread of the disease among the people in the province. So far, no case has been registered in the province."

According to the World Health Organization, the mortality rate for hemorrhagic fever reaches 40% of victims.

The virus is transmitted to humans through poultry or livestock, infecting a person through direct contact with blood, secretions, organs, or other body fluids.

Some types of viral hemorrhagic fevers: Dengue Fever, Ebola Fever, Lassa Fever, Marburg Fever and Yellow Fever.

It should be noted that there is no cure for viral hemorrhagic fevers, but some of them have vaccines, while prevention is the best way to combat them until scientists find additional vaccines.

Iraq officially recorded the 1st death in 2018 from the disease.

[Byline: Nadia Barnett]

--
Communicated by:
ProMED

[Crimean-Congo hemorrhagic fever is a widespread disease caused by a tick-borne virus (Nairovirus) of the Bunyaviridae family. The CCHF virus causes severe viral hemorrhagic fever outbreaks, with a case fatality rate of 10-40%.

Animals become infected by the bite of infected ticks and the virus remains in their bloodstream for about one week after infection, allowing the tick-animal-tick cycle to continue when another tick bites. Although a number of tick genera are capable of becoming infected with CCHF virus, ticks of the genus _Hyalomma_ are the principal vector.

The disease has been endemic to Iraq since 1979, with a few sporadic cases reported across the country. At times, small outbreaks have been reported, with the last outbreak happening in 2021 with 18 cases confirmed in Dhi Qar and Nineveh Governorates. (http://www.emro.who.int/pandemic-epidemic-diseases/news/who-builds-capacity-of-rapid-response-team-in-iraq-with-a-focus-on-crimean-congo-haemorrhagic-fever.html)

In early April 2022, the Public Health Department in Dhi Qar announced recording about 20 cases of hemorrhagic fever in the governorate since the beginning of 2022 and on 20 Apr 2022, the 1st laboratory-confirmed death was reported in Al-Meshkhab district in Al-Najaf governorate.

It is important to raise awareness about the risk factors of the disease, particularly in the population groups likely to be exposed to the virus, and educate them to take precautionary measures to reduce exposure to the virus, such as wearing gloves and protective clothing while handling animals.

Furthermore, appropriate capacity building and training of public health rapid response teams (RRT) should be carried out in order to equip them to control any future outbreaks of this anthropo-zoonotic disease. - Mod.UBA

